post_text:
It is imperative that students remain engaged with their remote learning assignments. We appreciate the efforts of both students and parents in this regard. To provide you with an update on your student’s progress, 4th marking period mid term grades will be posted in Firefly on Friday, May 1st for students in grades 5-12. Grades will be posted as an Outstanding, Satisfactory, or Unsatisfactory. Your interest in your student’s education is extremely important. If you have any issues accessing Firefly for grades, please contact your building principal.

We continue to discuss plans regarding end of the year activities. Our most important end of the year activity is Graduation. We are exploring all options concerning graduation. This includes the possibility of a traditional graduation with social distancing, a graduation for seniors with social distancing without spectators, and as a last resort, we are preparing a virtual graduation. We will do everything possible to honor our seniors unless otherwise directed by Governor Wolf.

post_text: We have just been notified by Governor Wolf that all schools are now closed through June. We will continue our current plan to provide continuity of education through planned instruction for the remainder of the academic year. Your continued support of our efforts to provide remote learning for our students is greatly appreciated. As a reminder, third marking period report cards will be posted in Firefly on Wednesday, April 15th for all students.

post_text: As we continue to address the challenges associated with COVID-19, we want to inform you, should we be unable to return to school on March 30th, our staff is preparing to provide online instruction for students in grades 3-12. For our primary students in grades K-2, we are planning to mail home instructional materials. If your child does not have his or her chromebook at home or access to a device, please contact your building principal. A grab and go breakfast/lunch combo two-day meal will be provided at no cost to all students on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays from 11:30am to 1pm at all elementary buildings. As additional information is provided to us from state officials, we will communicate with you immediately.

Good afternoon nighthawks. This is Dr. John Scola, Superintendent. To ensure the health, safety, and well-being of our students and staff, and to do our part in trying to mitigate the spread of COVID-19 throughout the District community and region, all Hanover Public School District schools will be closed from March 16, 2020, through March 27, 2020. Please note that all schools in York, Adams, and Franklin Counties are closed as well. An informational letter will be sent to you electronically as well as posted on social media sites and the district web page. Thank you for your understanding. It is sincerely appreciated.

Good Evening Nighthawks. This is Dr. John Scola, Superintendent of Schools for the Hanover Public School District. This is a Coronavirus update. We are carefully monitoring this constantly evolving situation and acquiring knowledgeable guidance from medical experts and local and state officials about how to best proceed. Tomorrow morning, superintendents from across the state will be in communication with Pennsylvania Secretary of Education, Pedro Rivera.

Based on the information gathered from the Secretary’s communication, the district will be sending out correspondence tomorrow afternoon outlining additional measures to ensure the safety and well-being of our staff and students.

post_text: There has been a widespread power outage that has affected Hanover Street Elementary and the surrounding area. The building is warm, with auxiliary lighting, hot water, and working restrooms. Lunch will be served. It is in the best interest of the students to remain here at school due to the widespread outage. Students and staff will remain in the building and instruction will continue. A Robo call for HST is underway.

post_text: The police have identified the source of the threat which was not credible. Tomorrow's show will go on at 2 and all tickets for tonight's show will be honored at that time. If you are unable to make the show we will arrange for refunds. We are sorry for the inconvenience and pleased that everyone is safe. We wish to thank the Hanover Borough Police for their prompt attention to this matter.

post_text: The district became aware of a threat against Hanover High School on social media. The police were immediately contacted and are investigating. Regretfully, due to the safety concern, we are postponing tonight's 7 p.m. musical performance. We will send out another robocall as we determine if the Sunday performance will be held. We apologize for any inconvenience to our community and performers. Safety must be our number one priority.
